editorial:
**O(n^2) DP**: `dp[i]` = length of LIS ending at index `i`. For each i, scan all j < i; if `ratings[j] < ratings[i]`, candidate is `dp[j]+1`.

```javascript
function longestTripStreak(ratings) {
  const n = ratings.length;
  if (n === 0) return 0;
  const dp = new Array(n).fill(1);
  let best = 1;
  for (let i = 1; i < n; i++) {
    for (let j = 0; j < i; j++) {
      if (ratings[j] < ratings[i]) dp[i] = Math.max(dp[i], dp[j] + 1);
    }
    best = Math.max(best, dp[i]);
  }
  return best;
}
```

**O(n log n) patience sort**: Maintain `tails`, where `tails[k]` is the smallest possible tail of any LIS of length `k+1`. For each value, binary-search the leftmost tail >= value (lower bound) and replace it; if not found, append.

```javascript
function longestTripStreak(ratings) {
  const tails = [];
  for (const x of ratings) {
    let lo = 0, hi = tails.length;
    while (lo < hi) {
      const m = (lo + hi) >> 1;
      if (tails[m] < x) lo = m + 1; else hi = m;
    }
    if (lo === tails.length) tails.push(x); else tails[lo] = x;
  }
  return tails.length;
}
```

**Time**: O(n^2) or O(n log n). **Space**: O(n).

For strict increase use `<` comparison (lower_bound).

