editorial:
**Reduction**: Keep the longest strictly increasing subsequence; delete the rest. Answer = `n - LIS_strict(nums)`.

**LIS via patience sort (O(n log n))**: maintain `tails`, where `tails[k]` = smallest possible tail of any increasing subsequence of length `k+1`. For each x, binary-search the leftmost tail >= x (lower bound) and replace; if not found, append.

```javascript
function minDeletionsSorted(nums) {
  const tails = [];
  for (const x of nums) {
    let lo = 0, hi = tails.length;
    while (lo < hi) {
      const m = (lo + hi) >> 1;
      if (tails[m] < x) lo = m + 1; else hi = m;
    }
    if (lo === tails.length) tails.push(x); else tails[lo] = x;
  }
  return nums.length - tails.length;
}
```

**Time**: O(n log n). **Space**: O(n).

With strict LIS, lower_bound (replace at first `>= x`) prevents duplicates from extending the LIS.
